1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {The Trompovsky, Rune's latest darling, which he has used
with aggressive success, even beating Simen Agdestein.} Ne4 {I preferred the
solid} (2... d5 {against Joel Benjamin in the Moskva OL, but now had had time
to prepare something a bit sharper.}) 3. Bf4 c5 4. d5 Qb6 5. Nd2 Qxb2 {I
preferred this to} (5... Nxd2 6. Bxd2 Qxb2 7. e4 {when white gets an obvious
initiative, though both are playable.}) 6. Nxe4 Qb4+ 7. c3 $5 {An interesting
move which prevents black from using the d4 or a4 squares for his Q.} Qxe4 8.
e3 e6 9. dxe6 Qxe6 {A strong move, I believe. Recapturing with the fP exposes
the kingside, and with the dP, black would lose his grip on the center.} 10.
Nf3 Be7 11. Bd3 b6 $1 {The beginning of a good plan. Black leaves the dP on d7
where it keeps his position solid. The advance ...d7-d5 would allow white to
open the position with e4 or c4 later, which would be very dangerous since it
will be long before black catches up in development.} 12. Qc2 g6 13. h4 $1 {
Although white has no concrete compensation for his P, he has achieved a very
complicated position, and this gives black more problems to solve.} Bb7 14. h5
Rg8 15. hxg6 hxg6 16. Rd1 $5 (16. O-O-O {was possible, but white's king
position would not necessarily be better on the queenside.}) 16... Nc6 17. Ng5
Bxg5 18. Bxg5 {Now white's compensation is becoming more obvious - the bishop
pair and the h-line - but black remains solid and has a secure grip on the
center, not to mention an extra pawn, to counterbalance this.} Ne5 (18... Qg4
19. Bf6 Qxg2 20. Rh4 {gives white a very dangerous attack. Black should avoid
adventures, and aim at consolidating his position.}) 19. Be4 d5 (19... Bc6 $5 {
was tempting, but as time grows shorter, one feels the need to get active.})
20. Bd3 (20. Bxd5 $5 {deserved serious attention, though to be honest, I
didn't notice it. Rune rejected it because of the variation} Bxd5 21. Qd2 f6 {
(The Bd5 cannot move due to mate on d8.)} (21... Rd8 $5 {(!!) is the move
which occurred to me when Rune mentioned the variation after the game. It is a
bizarre way of defusing the threat on d8. After} 22. Bxd8 $2 (22. e4 Rd7 $1 {
also appears to refute the sacrifice.}) 22... Bxg2 {appears to win,
threatening R, Q and K. Rune's intuition did not let him down.}) 22. Qxd5 Qxd5
23. Rxd5 Kf7 24. Bf4 Ke6 {when black's position is preferable. The N will be a
monster on c4, his K is more active and the h-line can be regained. But}) (20.
Qa4+ $2 Bc6 (20... Nd7 $1 {wins.}) 21. Qxc6+ $5 {did occur to me but}) 20...
Bc6 21. Be2 f6 22. Bf4 O-O-O 23. a4 {Both players were already running short
of time, so the rest of the game is a bit chaotic. The text is a logical way
to increase the confusion factor.} Rh8 24. Rg1 {Black now has something close
to complete control. Development is completed, the K relatively safe and the
h-line in hand. The only problem is making progress. Any violent action - for
example the natural continuation} Rh4 $5 (24... g5 $5 25. Bg3 f5 {preparing an
assault on the white king, raises the real possibility of the Bg3 becoming
devastatingly strong, since the Ne5 is less stable. I decided to take control
of the queenside and leave the center intact, though this also has drawbacks,
as seen later.}) 25. a5 b5 26. a6 g5 27. Bg3 Ra4 28. Rh1 Rxa6 29. Rh7 Ra4 (
29... Rd7 30. Rh8+ Kb7 31. f4 $1 {is unpleasant for black, f.eks.} gxf4 32.
exf4 Nc4 33. f5 {and disaster arrives on b8. That is why I decided to built a
haven on a6 for my K.}) 30. Bd3 $1 {Since black does not want both B entering
his position, he must agree to opposite colored B, guaranteeing white
attacking chances, especially since a real time-scramble was inevitable.} Nxd3+
31. Qxd3 Rd7 32. Rxd7 {Another unpleasant surprise. I had not taken exchanges
to be dangerous, but now it is easier for white to create threats around my
king.} Bxd7 $5 {Black offers the d-pawn to ensure king safety, and also plans
to transfer the Q to b6 later. Rune continues to find more frightening moves.}
33. Qh7 $5 Ra2 $1 {Good - this creates a path for the black K into white's
position if he needs to go for a long walk, and also creates a counterattack.}
34. Qh8+ Kb7 (34... Qe8 $5 {was suggested by Rune afterwards. the point is that
} 35. Qxf6 $2 {fails to} (35. Qh7 Qe4) (35. Qh6 $5 {the position remains messy,
f. eks.} Bg4 $2 36. Qxf6 $1 Bxd1 37. Qd6 {with enough attack to draw since} Kb7
{is met by} 38. Qxd5+) 35... Qh5 {but after}) 35. Qb8+ Ka6 36. Kf1 {If white's
K reaches g1 he can attack without distraction.} Qb6 37. Rxd5 $6 {With flags
hanging, Rune decides to cash in, but does not solve all of his problems. I
feared} (37. Qf8 {though the fearless} b4 $5 {may favor black. At this stage,
two hands were playing, and not so many brains.}) 37... Qxb8 38. Bxb8 Bc6 39.
Rxc5 Ra1+ 40. Ke2 Bxg2 41. Rf5 Bf1+ $1 {The sealed move, which Rune
underestimated. I thought at first black had a winning advantage, but analysis
convinced me that this was optimistic.} 42. Kd2 Kb7 43. Bd6 a5 44. Kc2 $1 (44.
Rxf6 Bc4 45. Kc2 a4 46. Kb2 Ra2+ 47. Kb1 a3 {and the aP will prove too
dangerous. This is the type of position that led me to be optimistic, but Rune
defends better.}) 44... Ra2+ $1 {The beginning of a crafty plan. The
straightforward} (44... Bc4 45. Kb2 $1 Ra2+ 46. Kb1 a4 {no longer works due
the pressure against b5. Here the simplest for white is} 47. Be7 {since} (47.
Rxb5+ Kc6 $1 48. Rc5+ Kxd6 49. Rxc4 Rxf2 50. Rxa4 f5 51. Kc1 Re2 $1 {should
win for black.})) 45. Kb1 Rd2 46. Rxf6 Bd3+ $1 {Giving white an unpleasant
choice. If white goes to the c-file the c3P falls, though this may be the best
chance. On the a-file, there are tactical problems on the last rank, and with .
..a3 becoming possible due to ...Ra2+.} 47. Ka1 g4 $1 {Creating the additional
worry of ...Be4-f3, attacking f2. White also has to worry about ..Rc2, aand
the advance of the aP.} 48. Be5 Bc4 49. Rf4 a4 50. Rxg4 a3 51. Rg1 Kb6 $1 {
A fine move that guarantees the decisive invasion. The reflex} (51... Rxf2 52.
Bd6 Kb6 53. Bb4 {keeps out the black K and may draw.}) 52. e4 {White jettisons
his P to bring the B back to defend. The race} (52. f4 Ka5 53. f5 Ka4 54. f6
Kb3 55. Rb1+ Rb2 56. f7 Bd3 $1 {ends in mate.} (56... Bxf7 57. c4)) 52... Ka5
53. Bf4 Rxf2 54. Bc1 Ka4 55. e5 Kb3 {Threatening ...Ra2+ and ...Bd3 matt.} 56.
Rd1 Be6 57. Bd2 Kc2 58. Be3 Re2 59. Rc1+ Kb3 60. Rb1+ Kxc3 {The double threat
to e3 and a2 wins.} 61. Rxb5 Rxe3 62. Rb1 Re2 $1 {There are certain technical
difficulties without white's eP due to stalemate possibilities, and I had no
desire to complicate my life. With the eP, white is quickly mated.} 63. Rg1 Rd2
$1 64. Re1 Bc4 65. e6 Kb3 {and white resigned in view of the familiar attack} (
65... Kb3 66. e7 (66. Rb1+ Rb2 67. e7 Kc2 {or ...Bd3}) 66... Bd3 67. Rb1+ Rb2)
0-1

